05309nam a22007575i 9780292768277DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927682777 a10.7560/7608752doi  a(DE-B1597)587254  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHN120.C48bS73 2015 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.4209722231 aStaudt, Kathleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCourage, Resistance, and Women in Ciudad Juárez :bChallenges to Militarization /cZulma Y. Méndez, Kathleen Staudt. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter One. Introduction: Conceptualizing Courage and Resistance in a Mired Human Rights Context -- tChapter Two. Historicizing and Contextualizing the Place: Three Historic Junctures -- tChapter Three From Fear and Intimidation to Game-Changing Activism -- tChapter Four “Fed Up” with Militarization and Murders, via Social Media -- tChapter Five. Toward Transnational Solidarity: Contesting the Border Narrative in a U.S. Congressional Race, Tribunals, and Faith-Based Activism -- tAfterword -- tAppendix One. Responsible Firearms Retailer Partnership: A 10-Point Voluntary Code -- tAppendix Two. Resolution (El Paso City Council) -- tAppendix Three. Resolution (City of Los Angeles) -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCiudad Juárez has recently become infamous for its murder rate, which topped 3,000 in 2010 as competing drug cartels grew increasingly violent and the military responded with violence as well. Despite the atmosphere of intimidation by troops, police, and organized criminals, women have led the way in civil society activism, spurring the Juárez Resistance and forging powerful alliances with anti-militarization activists. An in-depth examination of la Resistencia Juarense, Courage, Resistance, and Women in Ciudad Juárez draws on ethnographic research to analyze the resistance’s focus on violence against women, as well as its clash with the war against drugs championed by Mexican President Felipe Calderón with the support of the United States. Through grounded insights, the authors trace the transformation of hidden discourses into public discourses that openly challenge the militarized border regimes. The authors also explore the advocacy carried on by social media, faith-based organizations, and peace-and-justice activist Javier Sicilia while Calderón faced U.S. political schisms over the role of border trade in this global manufacturing site. Bringing to light on-the-ground strategies as well as current theories from the fields of sociology, political anthropology, and human rights, this illuminating study is particularly significant because of its emphasis on the role of women in local and transnational attempts to extinguish a hot zone. As they overcome intimidation to become game-changing activists, the figures featured in Courage, Resistance, and Women in Ciudad Juárez offer the possibility of peace and justice in the wake of seemingly irreconcilable conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHuman rightszMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aHuman rightszMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aMilitarismzMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aMilitarismzMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aSocial movementszMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aSocial movementszMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aViolencezMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aViolencezMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aWomenxViolence againstzMexicozCiudad Juárez. 0aWomenxViolence againstzMexic